accessrestrict.head: Restrictions on Access
accessrestrict.p: Series 1, 4, and 5 are closed for 75 years from date of record creation. Series 8 contains confidential employee and faculty informaiton and must be reviewed by an archivist prior to use by researchers.

Series 3 is closed for 100 years from date of record creation. Access to student records is governed by the federal Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act (FERPA), which protects the privacy of student education records.

bioghist.head: Historical or Biographical Note
bioghist.p: The Physics Department is a part of the Columbian College of Arts and Sciences. Physics, although not always called physics, was taught at Columbian College during the 1820s.

During the freshman and sophomore years, studies included English, Latin, and Greek; geography; arithmetic and algebra; history and antiquities; exercises in reading, speaking and composition; elements of chronology; rhetoric and logic; logarithms, geometry, trigonometry and mensuration; surveying, navigation, conic sections and Euclid's Elements. In his junior and senior years, the student took natural philosophy, astronomy, chemistry, fluxions, natural history, history of civil society, natural religion, Revelation, natural and political law, metaphysics, moral philosophy and analogy of religion to nature.

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Materials in this collection include office files, memos, curriculum lists, staff files, recommendations, correspondence, course materials, budget summaries, staff papers, university committee on research, student/faculty files, progress reports, contracts, administration materials, graduate applicants, speaker invitation letters, conferences/workshops, summaries of fiscal year, course syllabi. The collection covers the years 1930 to 2005. Note: Not all series are processed. Ask staff for assistance.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: This collection is organized into nine series. Seven are office/departmental files differentiated only by their date of transfer to the archives; one is a series of facilities plan; one is a series of faculty records.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series includes office files, memos, curriculum lists, staff files, recommendations, etc. from 1962-89.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains articles, announcements, correspondence, reports, invitation, press releases, and brochures. They range in date from 1935 to 2000. The materials concern Washington Conferences on Theoretical Physics, Dr. Niels Bohr, invitation lists, conference planning, Carnegie Institution of Washington, The George Washington University School of Engineering's "Engineering Form", the Physics Department, physics courses, and lecture series.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Files covering department administrative matters such as the evolution of the department's graduate programs, the creation and recruitment for new faculty positions, announcements, and departmental meetings. Also includes a file on the university-wide Information Technology Advisory Council, 1998-1999.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: These files contain confidential employee and faculty information, and must be reviewed by an archivist prior to use by researchers.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains documents from Professors William Parke and Raymond Seeger. The material includes research, published works by Parke and Seeger, course material, Sigma Xi documents, and papers from other physicists. The material dates between 1930-1995.
